{"type":"message","id":"d140b631","parentId":"c6c0ec6c","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:10:30.316Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_o4aztonuw5n1_1","toolName":"process","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[LLM] response length: 3868\n[master e24093b] pulse: 2026-03-24 161011\n 4 files changed, 195 insertions(+), 126 deletions(-)\n create mode 100644 memory/session/pulse_2026-03-24 161011.md\n rename mutations/{proposed => rejected}/2026-03-24 160909.mutation (100%)\n[sandbox pulse] 2026-03-24 161011 - Phase 1's immediate next task is Conditional Content Analysis - the empirical test to distinguish Pattern Information (CFI) from Causal Information. This is the experiment that will determine whether high-CFI tokens like \"compression\" and \"causal\" are genuinely causal or just scaffolding.\n\nProcess exited with code 0."}],"details":{"status":"completed","sessionId":"lucky-ocean","exitCode":0,"aggregated":"[LLM] response length: 3868\n[master e24093b] pulse: 2026-03-24 161011\n 4 files changed, 195 insertions(+), 126 deletions(-)\n create mode 100644 memory/session/pulse_2026-03-24 161011.md\n rename mutations/{proposed => rejected}/2026-03-24 160909.mutation (100%)\n[sandbox pulse] 2026-03-24 161011 - Phase 1's immediate next task is Conditional Content Analysis - the empirical test to distinguish Pattern Information (CFI) from Causal Information. This is the experiment that will determine whether high-CFI tokens like \"compression\" and \"causal\" are genuinely causal or just scaffolding.\n","name":"powershell C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774383030313}}
{"type":"message","id":"f8f277a7","parentId":"d140b631","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:10:30.319Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_o4aztonuw5n1_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 160909\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\n\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state:\r\n\r\n1. Phase 0 COMPLETE: Sandbox foundation established\r\n2. Phase 1 IN PROGRESS: Compression primitives - CFI analysis complete, next is conditional content analysis\r\n\r\nThe core breakthrough is that CFI ≠ Causal Discovery - these are different information quantities. The immediate next experiment is Conditional Content Analysis.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what concrete action I can take:\r\n\r\nThe Conditional Content Analysis experiment:\r\n- For moderate-frequency tokens (freq=60-80%), split pulse pairs into T-present and T-absent groups\r\n- Question: does research content of next-pulse differ between groups?\r\n- Candidate tokens: \"compression\" (freq=199, CFI=0.995), \"causal\" (freq=162, CFI=0.981), \"phase\" (freq=187, CFI=0.946)\r\n- If no difference: CFI measures scaffolding. If yes: tokens are genuinely causal.\r\n\r\nI need to:\r\n1. Parse the existing pulse files to extract pairs (pulse_n, pulse_{n+1})\r\n2. For each candidate token, split pairs into T-present and T-absent groups\r\n3. Analyze if there's a difference in the research content between groups\r\n\r\nBut first, I should check what pulse files exist and understand their format. Let me create a concrete plan:\r\n\r\n1. First, I need to understand the pulse file structure\r\n2. Then create an analysis script or document that describes the experiment methodology\r\n3. Potentially run initial analysis on a few tokens\r\n\r\nGiven the stateless nature and the 35-40s per pulse constraint, I should focus on creating a solid experimental design document that can be executed in the next pulse.\r\n\r\nLet me create a document that outlines the Conditional Content Analysis experiment with concrete methodology.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis is complete, but we still need empirical evidence distinguishing Pattern Information (CFI) from true Causal Information. The Conditional Content Analysis experiment is the critical next step to resolve this.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a concrete experimental design document for Conditional Content Analysis with methodology, token selection criteria, and expected outcomes based on the theory.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # Conditional Content Analysis Experiment\r\n**Date:** 2026-03-24\r\n**Status:** READY TO EXECUTE\r\n\r\n## Objective\r\nEmpirically distinguish **Pattern Information** (CFI - token predicts next token) from **Causal Information** (token causes next-pulse content change).\r\n\r\n## Core Question\r\nFor a token T that appears in ~60-80% of pulses:\r\n- Split all pulse pairs (P_n, P_{n+1}) into two groups: T present in P_n vs T absent\r\n- **If** research content differs between groups → T is causally relevant\r\n- **If** research content is identical → T is scaffolding (CFI measures prediction only)\r\n\r\n## Candidate Tokens (freq ~120-160 range to avoid constant-format trap)\r\n| Token | Freq | CFI | Rationale |\r\n|-------|------|-----|-----------|\r\n| `phase` | 187 | 0.946 | Research trajectory marker |\r\n| `causal` | 162 | 0.981 | Concept under investigation |\r\n| `compression` | 199 | 0.995 | Already appears almost everywhere (too high) |\r\n| `token` | 145 | 0.990 | Abstraction level discussion |\r\n\r\n**Note:** Exclude tokens with freq ≥ 190 (constant-format trap - metaprogramming artifacts).\r\n\r\n## Methodology\r\n\r\n### Step 1: Parse Pulse Pairs\r\nExtract all (P_n, P_{n+1}) pairs from pulse_2026-03-24*.md files.\r\n- Total pairs available: ~180 (from 181 pulses)\r\n- Expected execution: single pulse can process all pairs\r\n\r\n### Step 2: Group by Token Presence\r\nFor each candidate token T:\r\n- Group A: P_n contains T\r\n- Group B: P_n does NOT contain T\r\n- Minimum sample size: 20 per group for statistical validity\r\n\r\n### Step 3: Analyze Next-Pulse Content\r\nExtract \"research content\" from P_{n+1} by removing:\r\n- Header scaffolding (timestamps, pulse IDs, format markers)\r\n- Constant-format tokens (identified in prior analysis)\r\n- Keep: substantive research terms, discovered insights, next actions\r\n\r\n**Metrics:**\r\n1. Jaccard similarity of research vocab between Group A and Group B next-pulses\r\n2. Topic clustering (manual if automated fails)\r\n3. Difference in stated goals/resolutions\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcomes\r\n\r\n### Outcome A: No Difference Detected\r\n**Interpretation:** CFI=0.98 means perfect prediction but zero causal influence.\r\n- Tokens like \"phase\", \"causal\" are metaprogramming scaffolding\r\n- CFI measures Pattern Information (Layer 1) not Causal Information (Layer 2)\r\n- Compression can safely use CFI; causal discovery needs Transfer Entropy\r\n- **Implication:** Layer 2 needs different metric entirely\r\n\r\n### Outcome B: Significant Difference Detected\r\n**Interpretation:** Token presence genuinely changes next-pulse content.\r\n- Tokens are causally relevant, not just predictive\r\n- Need to quantify causal strength: P(content | do(T)) vs P(content | do(¬T))\r\n- **Implication:** CFI captures some causal signal, not just pattern\r\n\r\n### Outcome C: Ambiguous (Needs More Data)\r\n**Interpretation:** Effect size small or inconsistent.\r\n- Need more pulses (target ~2000 for reliable Transfer Entropy)\r\n- Current corpus insufficient for causal inference\r\n- **Implication:** Proceed with Transfer Entropy implementation as planned\r\n\r\n## Execution Plan\r\n\r\n### Immediate (Next Pulse)\r\n1. List all pulse files: `ls pulse_*.md`\r\n2. Parse and extract token frequencies from\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 16:09:33\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774383030316}}
